prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
In order to probe the full range in cool, i.e. atomic and molecular, gas reservoirs present and properly characterize the scatter, we aim to detect all galaxies at least at 5sigma or obtain a meaningful (3sigma) upper limits in case of non-detections. Fig.3 shows the average observed flux in the MIPS 24um, PACS 100um and 160um imaging together with two representative SEDs for star forming galaxies with colder (DH02: Dale & Helou 2002) and warmer dust temperatures (CE01: Chary & Elbaz 2001). Both templates provide good fits implying that most of our targets should indeed be dusty star formers. The expected average flux density is ~0.8mJy in ALMA band 6. Anchoring the IR SED at our measured MIPS 24um results in expected 1mm continuum emission in the range of 0.3 to 4 mJy. Standard calibration and bandpass accuracy are sufficient for this project.
Observed frequency and resolution -- The rest-frame 250-350um sub-mm continuum is shifted to 240-210GHz for sources at z=4-3 (i.e. inverted order of redshift bounds). Therefore, ALMA band 6 with a center wavelength of 240GHz is ideal. We request a resolution of 2'', i.e. 14-16kpc, to be sensitive to the bulk of the cool gas. Based on high resolution studies (e.g. Hodge et al. 2012) this is well-matched to typical source sizes of the molecular gas reservoir (that should strongly dominated the cool gas content at these redshifts; Obreschkow et al. 2009).
Correlator set-up -- As we require only continuum detections, we will use the TDM mode that provides an instantaneous bandwidth of 7.5GHz. We request to keep the spectral resolution to allow for chance detections of emission lines arising from sources within our fields.
Sensitivity -- A SFR of 100M_sun/yr with a depletion time of t_dep =0.8Gyr translates into an expected flux density of 270uJy at rest-frame 250um continuum (i.e. observed frame of 240GHz) assuming a bandwidth of 7.5GHz. We obtain consistent numbers using either the empirically relation of Groves et al. (2013) of log(M_gas[M_sun])=1.34+0.882log(L_250um[L_sun]) or by scaling the IR SED of such a system to z=4. Our estimated SFRs based on MIPS 24um detections (3sigma) lie between logSFR~2-4 (Fig. 2), thus the resulting expected continuum flux densities are in the range of 0.3 to 4.0 mJy (see also above). To detect even the faint end of our sources, we require an rms of 90uJy, i.e. a 3sigma detection of a z=4 galaxy with SFR=100M_sun/yr. Only ALMA can reach such an sensitivity in a reasonable amount of time, e.g. IRAM/PdBI would require >300x more on-source time alone.
Therefore we require 2.33min per source or a total of 5.44h 12m time to determine the cool gas content and its associated depletion time in a complete sample of 73 massive log(M_star)=10.5-11.0) main sequence galaxies past the peak of cosmic star formation activity.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We request rest-frame ~250um continuum observations of a complete sample of 86 massive (log(M_stellar/M_sun) > 10.5) normal star-forming, i.e. main sequence, galaxies at high redshift in an epoch of increasing SFR density (z~3-4) identified in the 2 sq.deg COSMOS field. Using our new, empirically calibrated correlation between mono-chromatic sub-mm luminosity and total gas content we will measure the cool gas mass in these systems. Combined with estimations of their star formation rates from the IR spectral energy distribution (and incoming high-sensitivity Jansky VLA radio continuum imaging), the gas depletion time, or its inverse - the star formation efficiency, of each galaxy will be derived. The proposed observations will provide the first solid measurement of the mean depletion time for normal star-forming galaxies beyond the peak of star formation activity (at z~2-3). A reduced depletion time (relative to local star-forming galaxies) has been inferred for z~1-2.5 samples, but conflicting results based on small (< 5) samples exist beyond these redshifts. These proposed observations are vital in providing the necessary constraints for current galaxy evolution models.
